<span id="freeTextContainer6267178070089077395">...Hamilton raises the stakes in <i>The Neutronium Alchemist</i>, as a middle book is supposed to do. It does more or less suffer from the same problems as the previous novel though. Bloated, repetitive and not very demanding. Although Hamilton tries to make it a multi-faceted conflict, he avoids the really big issue in the story in favour of politics and battles. That might be fine with some readers. I would have liked a little more from this novel but after <i>The Reality Dysfunction</i>, that was hardly wh</span>
  <span id="freeText6267178070089077395" style="display:none">...Hamilton raises the stakes in <i>The Neutronium Alchemist</i>, as a middle book is supposed to do. It does more or less suffer from the same problems as the previous novel though. Bloated, repetitive and not very demanding. Although Hamilton tries to make it a multi-faceted conflict, he avoids the really big issue in the story in favour of politics and battles. That might be fine with some readers. I would have liked a little more from this novel but after <i>The Reality Dysfunction</i>, that was hardly what one could expect....<br /><br /><a href="http://valsrandomcomments.blogspot.com/2017/05/the-neutronium-alchemist-peter-f.html" rel="nofollow noopener">Full Random Comments review</a></span>
