        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer673515401" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer600457794283044536">This is book 2 of a trilogy (or books 3-4 of a hexology if you buy the paperbacks) and it continues the space opera starting with The Reality Dysfunction. I&apos;m torn between giving it 2 stars or 3, because it was entertaining enough to keep reading, and I want to see what happens in the end, but wow this thing drags on. The book provides a handy &quot;cast of characters&quot; detailing exactly 150 names from the last book that you&apos;ll need to remember for this book. Call me simple, but I feel like the author</span>
  <span id="freeText600457794283044536" style="display:none">This is book 2 of a trilogy (or books 3-4 of a hexology if you buy the paperbacks) and it continues the space opera starting with The Reality Dysfunction. I'm torn between giving it 2 stars or 3, because it was entertaining enough to keep reading, and I want to see what happens in the end, but wow this thing drags on. The book provides a handy "cast of characters" detailing exactly 150 names from the last book that you'll need to remember for this book. Call me simple, but I feel like the author is complicating my life.<br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ <br /><br />I rolled my eyes when I realized that all the dead were coming back to life, but I went apoplectic when Al Capone emerged as a major character. And I almost burned the damned book when young Kung Fu Elvis started a shoving match with Fat Vegas Elvis in a bar. Come on.<br /><br />So pretty much the only reason to read this book is to get from book 1 to book 3 of the trilogy. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span></span>
